The '''Platine War''' (18 August 1851 – 3 February 1852) was fought between the [[Argentine Confederation]] and an alliance consisting of the [[Empire of Brazil]], [[Uruguay]] and the Argentine provinces of [[Entre Ríos Province|Entre Ríos]] and [[Corrientes Province|Corrientes]]. The war was part of a long-running interest disputes between Argentina and Brazil for influence over [[Uruguay]] and [[Paraguay]], and hegemony over the [[Platine region]] (areas bordering the [[Río de la Plata]]). The conflict took place in Uruguay, on the Río de la Plata, and northeastern Argentina. [[Uruguay]]'s internal troubles, including the long-running [[Uruguayan Civil War]], "''La Guerra Grande''" (The Great War), were heavily influential factors leading to the Platine War. 

In 1850, the Platine region was politically unstable. Although the Governor of Buenos Aires [[Juan Manuel de Rosas]] had used his political influence  to gain dictatorial control over other Argentine provinces, his rule was plagued by a series of regional rebellions. Meanwhile, Uruguay struggled with its own [[Uruguayan Civil War|civil war]] which started after getting independent from the Brazilian Empire in 1828 (no longer the Cisplatine Province) after conclusion of [[Cisplatine War]]. Rosas backed the Uruguayan [[National Party (Uruguay)|Blanco party]] in this conflict, and further desired to extend Argentine borders to areas formerly occupied by the Spanish [[Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata]]. This meant asserting control over Uruguay, Paraguay, and [[Bolivia]]. This threatened Brazilian interests and sovereignty since the old Spanish Viceroyalty had also included territories which had long been incorporated into Brazilian province of [[Rio Grande do Sul]].

Brazil actively pursued ways to eliminate threat from Rosas. In 1851, it allied with the Argentine breakaway provinces of [[Corrientes Province|Corrientes]] and [[Entre Ríos Province|Entre Rios]] (led by [[Justo José de Urquiza]]), and the anti-Rosas [[Colorado Party (Uruguay)|Colorado party]] in Uruguay. Brazil next secured the south-western flank by signing defensive alliances with [[Paraguay]] and [[Bolivia]]. Faced with an offensive alliance against his regime, Rosas declared war on Brazil. 

Allied forces first advanced into Uruguayan territory, defeating the Rosas supporters from the [[Blanco Party (Uruguay)|Blanco party]] led by [[Manuel Oribe]]. Afterwards, the Allied army was divided, with the main arm advancing by land to engage Rosas's main defenses and the other launching a seaborne assault directed at [[Buenos Aires]].

The Platine War ended in 1852 with the Allied victory at the [[Battle of Caseros]], for some time establishing Brazilian hegemony over much of [[South America]]. The war ushered a period of economic and political stability in the [[Empire of Brazil]]. With Rosas gone, Argentina began a political process which would result in a more unified state. However, the end of the Platine war did not completely resolve issues within the Platine region. Turmoil continued in subsequent years, with internal disputes among political factions in Uruguay, a long civil war in Argentina, and an emergent Paraguay asserting its claims. Two more major international wars (see:[[Paraguayan War]]) followed during the next two decades, sparked by territorial ambitions and conflicts over influence.

== Background ==
=== Rosas rule in Argentina ===
{{main|Argentine Civil War}}
[[File:Brazil and la Plata.png|thumb|left|250px|alt=map of South America with the Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata indicated in blue, the area of which incorporated portions of present-day Argentina, Uruguay, Brazil, Paraguay, Bolivia and Chile|Spain's [[Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata]] in blue, and [[Brazil|Portuguese-America]] in green. Viceroyalty was split among Argentina, Bolivia, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay after Wars of Independence.]]

[[Don (honorific)|Don]] [[Juan Manuel de Rosas]] became governor of [[Buenos Aires Province|Buenos Aires]] after the brief period of anarchy following the end of the [[Cisplatine War]] in 1828. In theory, Rosas only held as much power as governors of the other Argentine provinces, but in reality he ruled over the entire [[Argentina|Argentine Confederation]], as the country was then known. Although he was one of the [[Federales (Argentina)|Federalists]], a faction which demanded greater provincial autonomy, in practice Rosas exercised control over the other provinces and become the virtual dictator of Argentina.{{efn|name=Rosas rule}}{{efn|name=Rosas reign}}{{sfn|Vainfas|2002|p=447}} During his 20-year government, the country witnessed the resurgence of armed conflicts between the [[Unitarian Party|Unitarians]] (his rival political faction) and the Federalists.{{sfn|Vainfas|2002|p=447}}{{sfn|Holanda|1976|p=113}}{{sfn|Vianna|1994|p=528}}

Rosas desired to recreate the former [[Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata]]. He aimed to build a powerful, republican state with Argentina placed at the its center.{{efn|name=Rosas recovery}}{{efn|name=Rosas chefia}}{{efn|name=Rosas reconstituir}}{{efn|name=Rosas objetivo}}{{sfn|Estado-maior do Exército|1972|p=546}}{{sfn|Maia|1975|p=255}} The defunct Viceroyalty had shattered into several separate nations following the [[Argentine War of Independence]] at the beginning of the 19th century. To achieve reunification, the Argentine government needed to annex the three neighboring countries - [[Bolivia]], [[Uruguay]] and [[Paraguay]], as well as to incorporate a [[Rio Grande do Sul|portion of the southern region]] of [[Brazil]].{{sfn|Lyra 1977, Vol 1|p=160}} Rosas first had to gather allies across the region who shared his vision. In some instances, this meant that he had to become involved in the internal politics of neighboring countries, backing those sympathetic to union with Argentina, and occasionally even financing rebellions and wars.{{efn|name=Rosas manipulation}}{{sfn|Lyra 1977, Vol 1|p=160}}

===Paraguay===
Paraguay considered itself a sovereign nation since 1811, but it was not recognized as such by any other nation. Argentina viewed it as a rebellious province. The Paraguayan dictator [[José Gaspar Rodríguez de Francia]] decided that the best way to maintain his own rule and the independence of Paraguay from Argentina was to isolate the country from contacts with the outside world. It was for this reason that, up until 1840, Paraguay had avoided establishing diplomatic relations with other nations.{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=24}} With the death of Francia, this policy began to shift, and his successor Don [[Carlos Antonio López]] signed two treaties in July 1841. These were the "Friendship, Commerce and Navigation" and "Limits" agreements made with the Argentine province of [[Corrientes Province|Corrientes]], which itself had broken away from Argentina under Rosas.{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=26}} Meanwhile, Rosas increasingly put pressure on Paraguay. He continued to refuse to recognize Paraguayan independence and placed a blockade on international traffic to and from Paraguay on the [[Paraná River|Paraná river]].{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=26}}

=== Uruguayan conflict ===
{{main|Uruguayan Civil War}}
[[File:Rivera porteña.jpg|thumb|250px|alt=An old photograph showing buildings lining the river banks of the Rio de la Plata at Buenos Aires.|View of the [[Río de la Plata]] (River Plate) from [[Buenos Aires]], 1852. The Argentine capital was the center of Rosas' power.]]

The old Brazilian province of [[Cisplatina]] had become independent Oriental Republic of Uruguay after the [[Cisplatine War]] of the 1820s.{{sfn|Holanda|1976|p=113}} The country soon was engulfed in a long civil war between its two political parties: the [[National Party (Uruguay)|Blancos]], led by Don [[Juan Antonio Lavalleja]], and the [[Colorado Party (Uruguay)|Colorados]], led by Don [[Fructuoso Rivera]].{{sfn|Holanda|1976|p=113}}

Lavalleja soon discovered that Rosas in neighbouring Buenos Aires was interested in aiding him financially and militarily.{{sfn|Holanda|1976|p=113}} In 1832, Lavalleja began to receive aid{{sfn|Holanda|1976|pp=113, 114}} from [[Bento Gonçalves da Silva|Bento Gonçalves]], a soldier and farmer from the Brazilian province of [[Rio Grande do Sul]]. Gonçalves had been encouraged by Rosas [[Ragamuffin War|to rebel against the Brazilian government]] in 1835, with the ultimate aim of enabling Argentina to annex the province of [[Rio Grande do Sul]].{{sfn|Holanda|1976|p=116}}{{sfn|Vainfas|2002|p=448}} Together, Lavalleja and Gonçalves initiated a military campaign in Uruguay which was characterized by extensive violence and pillage.{{sfn|Holanda|1976|p=114}} Gonçalves betrayed Rosas and Lavalleja by becoming an ally of Rivera.{{sfn|Estado-maior do Exército|1972|p=546}}{{sfn|Holanda|1976|p=117}} Both then invaded Uruguay and overran most of the country outside the environs of the capital, [[Montevideo]]. Defeated, the then-Uruguayan president [[Manuel Oribe]], like the betrayed Lavalleja a member of the Blanco party,{{sfn|Holanda|1976|p=114}}{{sfn|Furtado|2000|p=7}} resigned his position as president and fled to Argentina.{{sfn|Holanda|1976|p=119}}

Rosas was determined to restore Argentine suzerainty over Uruguay and take revenge on Gonçalves. A series of interventions resulted. In 1839 an army led by Lavalleja, Oribe and [[Justo José de Urquiza]], (Governor of [[Entre Ríos Province|Entre Rios]]) was quickly defeated by Rivera. At this point, Lavalleja turned his back on the conflict and played no further part in the civil war.{{sfn|Holanda|1976|p=120}} Rosas sent another army of Argentines and Uruguayans in 1845, led by Oribe{{sfn|Furtado|2000|p=7}} and Urquiza,{{sfn|Estado-maior do Exército|1972|p=546}} and this time defeated Rivera's forces, slaughtering the survivors. Rivera was one of the few who managed to escape,{{sfn|Holanda|1976|p=121}} and went into exile in [[Rio de Janeiro]].{{sfn|Vainfas|2002|p=303}}{{sfn|Vianna|1994|p=526}} What remained of Rivera's Colorados held power only in the country's capital [[Montevideo]] as Oribe's forces began the [[Great Siege of Montevideo]].{{sfn|Holanda|1976|p=120}} The violence in Uruguay escalated, with Oribe's men killing more than 17,000 Uruguayans and 15,000 Argentinians during the conflict.{{sfn|Costa|2003|p=145}}

Oribe's control of nearly all of Uruguay had been secured, enabling him to launch an invasion of southern Brazil, his forces stealing cattle, looting ranches, and liquidating political enemies as they went.{{sfn|Vianna|1994|p=526}} More than 188 Brazilian farms were attacked, with 814,000 cattle and 16,950 horses stolen.{{sfn|Costa|2003|p=146}} Local Brazilians independently decided to retaliate, making raids into Uruguay which became known as "''Califórnias''",{{sfn|Estado-maior do Exército|1972|p=547}}{{sfn|Vianna|1994|p=527}}{{sfn|Pedrosa|2004|p=110}} in reference to the violence in western North America during [[California]]'s revolt against [[Mexico]], its brief independence and subsequent annexation by the U.S.{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=371}}{{sfn|Bueno|2003|p=207}} As conflict further escalated with the persistent support of Rosas for the Blancos, anarchy spread over wide areas in the region; with a growing threat to trade, the era's two greatest powers, [[France]] and [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|Great Britain]], were induced to declare war on Argentina and impose the [[Anglo-French blockade of the Río de la Plata]].{{sfn|Estado-maior do Exército|1972|p=546}} [[Buenos Aires]] suffered repeated attacks from Anglo-French fleets. The Argentine government was able to mount effective resistance, however, leading to a peace accord in 1849.{{sfn|Estado-maior do Exército|1972|p=547}}{{sfn|Lima|1989|p=158}}

=== Empire of Brazil reacts ===
[[File:Pedro II of Brazil 1851 edit.png|thumb|left|200px|alt=Half-length portrait from a photograph showing the young, bearded Emperor Pedro II in full uniform with sash of office and various medals|Emperor [[Pedro II of Brazil|Dom Pedro&nbsp;II]] around the time of the Platine War]]

By the middle of the 19th century, the Empire of Brazil was the richest{{sfn|Pedrosa|2004|p=232}} and most powerful nation in [[Latin America]].{{sfn|Pedrosa|2004|p=35}} It thrived under democratic institutions and a constitutional monarchy, and prided itself on the absence of the [[Caudillo|caudillos]], dictators and ''coups d'état'' which were common across the rest of the continent.{{efn|name=Brasil consolidando}} During the minority of emperor [[Pedro II of Brazil|Pedro&nbsp;II]] in the 1830s, however, there had been internal rebellions driven by local disputes for power within a few provinces.{{sfn|Dolhnikoff|2005|p=206}} One of these, the [[Ragamuffin War]], had been led by [[Bento Gonçalves da Silva|Gonçalves]], as noted above.

For the Brazilian Empire, expansionist plans on the part of powerful, republican Argentina represented an existential threat. It also signified a threat to Brazilian hegemony across its southern borders. A successful Argentine bid to incorporate Paraguay and Uruguay into a reconstituted [[Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata]] (and control of the Platine river network consequently passing into entirely hostile hands{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=28}}{{sfn|Furtado|2000|p=6}}) would have threatened to cut communication between the Brazilian province of [[Mato Grosso]] and Rio de Janeiro.{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=28}}{{sfn|Furtado|2000|p=6}} With river transportation denied, the alternative land routes would require months of travel instead of days. Nor was Brazil keen to share a direct border with Argentina, fearing an increased vulnerability to an invasion by Rosas.{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=28}}{{sfn|Furtado|2000|p=8}}

The members of the Brazilian Cabinet could not reach agreement as to how to address the danger posed by Rosas. Some ministers advocated seeking a peaceful resolution at any cost. These feared Brazil was unprepared for war and that a defeat would lead to a situation similar to the chaos following the loss of Cisplatine in the 1820s, which ended in abdication by [[Pedro I of Brazil|Dom Pedro I]], the Emperor's father. Other ministers took the position that only a military response would eliminate the threat. In 1849, however, [[Paulino José Soares de Sousa, Viscount of Uruguay|Paulino José Soares de Sousa]], a member of the pro-war faction and later Viscount of Uruguai, was chosen as the new minister of Foreign Affairs.{{sfn|Lyra 1977, Vol 1|pp=158–162}} Soares made clear his intent to deal with Argentina without foreign assistance, announcing that the "Imperial Government does not desire or judge convenient an alliance with France or any other European nation related to the matters in the Platine region. It understands that they must be resolved by the nations which [we] are closely connected with... It will not admit European influence over America." The Empire of Brazil was determined to extend its zone of influence over South America.{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=391}}

The cabinet settled upon a risky alternative to resolve the complicated situation in the Platine region. Instead of undertaking a period of conscription to build up the [[Brazilian Army]], which would have been costly, the Council decided to rely on the standing army. It sent a contingent south to secure the region. Brazil held an advantage in possessing a powerful and modern navy, along with an experienced professional army hardened by years of internal and external warfare.{{sfn|Costa|2003|p=148}} Up until this point, no other nation in South America possessed true navies or regular armies. Rosas' and Oribe's forces were largely made up of irregular troops on loan from those caudillos who supported them.{{sfn|Barroso|2000|p=119}} Even a decade later, Argentina could only field an army of 6,000 men.{{sfn|Furtado|2000|p=21}} Brazil also decided to adopt Rosas' own tactics by financing his opponents to weaken him both internally and externally.{{sfn|Maia|1975|p=255}}{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=390}}{{sfn|Holanda|1976|pp=114, 115}}

=== Alliance against Rosas ===
[[File:Urquiza (primer daguerrotipo).jpg|thumb|200px|alt=Half-length photographic portrait of a man dressed in a military-style tunic, open at the front.|[[Justo José Urquiza]], governor of [[Entre Ríos Province|Entre Rios]].]]

The Brazilian government set about creating a regional alliance against Rosas, sending a delegation to the region led by [[Honório Hermeto Carneiro Leão, Marquis of Paraná|Honório Hermeto Carneiro Leão]] (later the Marquis of Paraná), who held [[plenipotentiary]] authority. He was assisted by [[Viscount of Rio Branco|José Maria da Silva Paranhos]] (later the Viscount of Rio Branco). Brazil signed a treaty with Bolívia in which Bolivia agreed to strengthen its border defenses to deter any attack by Rosas, though it declined to contribute troops to a war with Argentina.{{sfn|Lima|1989|p=159}} 

Isolationist Paraguay was more difficult to win over. Brazil made the initial overtures, becoming the first country to formally recognise Paraguayan independence in 1844.{{sfn|Estado-maior do Exército|1972|p=546}} This soon led to the establishment of excellent diplomatic relations. The Brazilian ambassador in Paraguay, Pimenta Bueno, became a private councilor to President [[Carlos Antonio López]].{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=26}} A defensive alliance{{sfn|Lyra 1977, Vol 1|p=163}} was signed on 25 December 1850{{sfn|Estado-maior do Exército|1972|p=547}}{{sfn|Golin|2004|p=41}} between Brazil and Paraguay, in which López agreed to supply the Empire with horses for its army.{{sfn|Furtado|2000|p=8}} But Paraguay refused to contribute troops to fight Rosas, believing that [[Justo José Urquiza]] (who had invaded Uruguay in 1839 and in 1845), the ruler of the Argentine [[Entre Ríos Province|Entre Rios]] province, secretly wished to annex Paraguay.{{sfn|Furtado|2000|p=10}}

Brazil's involvement in the Uruguayan civil war also began to deepen. [[Luís Alves de Lima e Silva|Luis Alves de Lima e Silva]], the Count of Caxias, assumed the presidency (governorship) of [[Rio Grande do Sul]] and the command of the four Brazilian Army divisions headquartered in the province.{{sfn|Bueno|2003|p=207}} Beginning in 1849, the Imperial government directly assisted the besieged Uruguayan government of ''Colorados'' in [[Montevideo]], and on 6 September 1850 the Uruguayan representative Andres Lamas signed an agreement with [[Irineu Evangelista de Sousa]]{{efn|name=Viscount of Mauá}} to transfer money to the Montevideo government through his bank.{{sfn|Furtado|2000|p=8}}{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=387}}{{sfn|Golin|2004|p=35}} On 16 March 1851, the Empire of Brazil openly declared its support of ''Colorado'' government of Uruguay against Oribe, something it had been covertly doing for more than two years. This did not please the Argentine government, and it began mobilizing for war.{{sfn|Lyra 1977, Vol 1|p=163}}{{sfn|Maia|1975|p=256}}

Brazil had also been searching for support against Rosas inside Argentina, with some success. On 1 May 1851, the province of [[Entre Ríos Province|Entre Rios]], still governed by [[Justo José Urquiza|Urquiza]], declared to Rosas that "it is the will of its people to re-assume the entire exercise of its own sovereignty and power which had been delegated to the governor of Buenos Aires." It was followed by the province of Corrientes, governed by [[Benjamín Virasoro]], which sent the same message.{{sfn|Lyra 1977, Vol 1|p=164}} Brazil encouraged and financially supported both uprisings. One of the reasons for Urquiza's betrayal of Rosas was a long-running rivalry. Rosas had tried to remove him from power several times since 1845, suspecting that the caudillo was nurturing designs for his overthrow.{{sfn|Estado-maior do Exército|1972|p=547}} This was the trigger for military intervention, and Brazil sent a naval force to the Platine region, basing it near the port of [[Montevideo]]. The British Rear admiral [[John Pascoe Grenfell]], a veteran of the [[Independence of Brazil|Brazilian War of Independence]] and of the [[Cisplatine War]], was appointed to lead the fleet,{{sfn|Lima|1989|p=159}} which reached Montevideo on 4 May 1851. His command included 1 [[frigate]], 7 [[corvette]]s, 3 [[brig]]s and 6 [[steamboat|steamships]].{{sfn|Maia|1975|p=256}}{{sfn|Estado-maior do Exército|1972|p=548}} The Brazilian Armada had a total of 59 vessels of various types in 1851, including 36 armed sailing ships, 10 armed steamships, 7 unarmed sailing ships and 6 sailing transports.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=181}}

Uruguay, Brazil and the Argentine provinces of Entre Rios and Corrientes joined in an offensive Alliance against Rosas on 29 May 1851. The text of the treaty declared that the objective was to protect Uruguayan independence, pacify its territory, and expel Oribe's forces.{{sfn|Vianna|1994|p=527}} [[Justo José Urquiza|Urquiza]] would command the Argentine forces and [[Eugenio Garzón]] would lead the Colorado Uruguayans, with both receiving financial and military aid from the Empire of Brazil.{{sfn|Maia|1975|p=256}} 

This was followed on 2 August 1851 by landings of the first Brazilian detachments in Uruguay, consisting of approximately 300 soldiers of the 6th Battalion of Skirmishers sent to protect ''Fuerte del Cerro'' (Cerro Fort).{{sfn|Maia|1975|pp=256, 257}} In response, Rosas declared war against Brazil on 18 August 1851.{{sfn|Furtado|2000|p=9}}

According to Herrera y Obes, Rosas would have said, as war approached: "poor Brazilians, I'm going to make of their Emperor my butler".<ref>Herrera a Lamas, 28 de febrero de 1850 (Correspondencia Diplomáática de M. Herrera y
Obes, II 232)</ref>

